What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. The data contains numeric and categorical.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

This dataset contains 81 different variable for different findings

Main figurings to find out

  • What's income level for the borrowers?
  • Does Estimated Return varies from the BorrowerAPR?
  • What's the borrowers Credit Score?
  • Does Credit Score and Credit Rating influence the borrowers APR?
  • Does borrower Income has influence?
  • What are the Credit rating for Homeowner borrowers?
  • Does Lenders prefer borrowers with better Prosper Score ?
  • What's the relation between
    • Current and Completed Loans vs. Borrower Rate
    • Homeowner vs. Credit Rating
    • Income Range vs. Borrowers Rating
    • Credit Grades vs. BorrowerRate
    • Income Range vs. CreditScoreAve
    • Prosper Score vs. Credit Score Ave
    • Credit Rating vs. Income Range
    • Average Credit Score vs. BorrowerAPR
    • 'BorrowerAPR', 'ProsporScore' vs 'EstimatedReturn'
    • Relation between Borrowers Rate and Credit Rating during the Years
    • Average Credit Score vs. Borrower APR vs. Loan Term
    • Estimated Loss vs BorrowerAPR

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

This dataset have so much to explore:

  • 1- IncomeRange divided income classes
  • 2- BorrowerAPR Borrower annual interest rate
  • 3- BorrowerRate: The Borrower's interest rate for the current loan.
  • 4- CreditGrade: Credit Ranks
  • 5- ProsperRating : Borrower Ranks at Prosper
  • 6- EstimatedReturn: Annual Estimated interest rate
  • 7- Year Loans Year
  • 8- LoanStatus: status of the loans
  • 9- CreditScoreAve: the average between the 'CreditScoreRangeLower', 'CreditScoreRangeUpper'.
  • 10- EstimatedEffectiveYield: the return on loans that has its interest payments
  • 11- IsBorrowerHomeowner: If the Borrower own a home and posibility of mortgage
  • 12- Term Loan term by months
  • 13- Estimated Loss

Propser Credit Rate & Credit Grades¶

The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA - HR. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

As for the Credit Grade is Credit rating that was assigned in tome of the application

So the idea here is to combine both into one variable column, as they are compeleting each other.

Relationship Chart¶

In [63]:
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (10,7);

def heatmap(x, y, size):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    
    # Mapping from column names to integer coordinates
    x_labels = [v for v in sorted(x.unique())]
    y_labels = [v for v in sorted(y.unique())]
    x_to_num = {p[1]:p[0] for p in enumerate(x_labels)} 
    y_to_num = {p[1]:p[0] for p in enumerate(y_labels)} 
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8), dpi=80)
    size_scale = 1000

    ax.scatter(
        x=x.map(x_to_num), # Use mapping for x
        y=y.map(y_to_num), # Use mapping for y
        s=size * size_scale, # Vector of square sizes, proportional to size parameter
        marker='o', # Use square as scatterplot marker
        c='#467821'
    )
    
    # Show column labels on the axes
    ax.set_xticks([x_to_num[v] for v in x_labels])
    ax.set_xticklabels(x_labels, rotation=45, horizontalalignment='right')
    ax.set_yticks([y_to_num[v] for v in y_labels])
    ax.set_yticklabels(y_labels);
    
data = pld
columns = [ 'EstimatedReturn', 'CreditScoreAve', 'DebtToIncomeRatio', 'EstimatedEffectiveYield','BorrowerAPR', 'LoanOriginalAmount','EstimatedLoss'] 
corr = data[columns].corr()
corr = pd.melt(corr.reset_index(), id_vars='index') # Unpivot the dataframe, so we can get pair of arrays for x and y
corr.columns = ['x', 'y', 'value']
heatmap(
    x=corr['x'],
    y=corr['y'],
    size=corr['value'].abs()
);

<Figure size 640x640 with 0 Axes>

In this Heating map shows the relationship between 5 different variable: 'EstimatedReturn', 'CreditScoreAve', 'DebtToIncomeRatio', 'EstimatedEffectiveYield','BorrowerAPR'. We see that Credit Score doesn't get influenced with Debt ration. On the other hand, we found that strongest positive relation is between 'DebtToIncomeRatio', 'EstimatedEffectiveYield','BorrowerAPR'.

Also, the Estimated Loss has a positive relationship with BorrowerAPR, Estimated Yield. That lead Credit Score would really impact the Loan Amount, Yields, and Interest Rate.
